🟩 Small Company / Startup
👉 3 to 6 tickets per day
(less complex but more variety)
Examples:
	• Restart service
	• Fix CI/CD pipeline error
	• Check disk space
	• Add IAM user
	• Fix deployment failure

🟨 Medium Company
👉 2 to 4 tickets per day
(more structured work)
Examples:
	• Deploy new application version
	• Update Terraform module
	• Fix Docker image issue
	• Configure ALB or route53
	• Investigate pod crash in Kubernetes

🟥 Large Company / MNC (AWS + Kubernetes environment)
👉 1 to 3 tickets per day
(Because tickets are bigger and take time)
Examples:
	• Production issue (P1/P2)
	• Kubernetes scaling issue
	• CI/CD pipeline redesign
	• Update infrastructure modules
	• Debug auto-scaling or ALB error

🟦 During High Load Days
Sometimes you may get:
👉 5–10 small tickets
But these are usually very quick:
	• Reset password
	• Give S3 access
	• Fix IAM permission
	• Add EC2 tag
	• Add DNS record

🟧 During Production Incidents

You work on only 1 ticket but it may take many hours.
Examples:
	• Application downtime
	• ALB unhealthy targets
	• EC2 memory leak
	• Database high latency
	• Pod crash loop

⭐ So Final Answer:
👉 A Junior DevOps Engineer typically handles 2 to 5 tickets per day on average
👉 Sometimes more (5–10 small ones), sometimes just 1 big one

