In a real DevOps job (especially junior level) you usually handle 3 types of tickets:
1️⃣ Production Issues (Incidents)
2️⃣ Change Requests (Deployments / Updates)
3️⃣ Infrastructure / Automation Tasks
I'll show real ticket examples similar to what you would see in tools like
Jira, ServiceNow, or Azure DevOps.

1️⃣ Production Issue Tickets (Very Common)
These are urgent tickets when something breaks.
Example Ticket
Title: Website returning 502 error
Task:
Investigate why production website is down.
What you do
	1. SSH into server

ssh ec2-user@server-ip
	2. Check container

docker ps
	3. Check logs

docker logs container-id
	4. Restart service

docker restart container-id
	5. Verify

curl localhost

Another Real Ticket
Title: High CPU usage on EC2
Check server

top
Check memory

free -m
Check disk

df -h
Kill process if needed

kill -9 PID

2️⃣ Deployment Tickets (Very Common)
Example:
Title: Deploy new version of application to production.
Steps
1️⃣ Pull latest code

git pull origin main
2️⃣ Build docker image

docker build -t myapp:v2 .
3️⃣ Push to registry

docker push myrepo/myapp:v2
4️⃣ Update Kubernetes deployment

kubectl set image deployment/myapp myapp=myrepo/myapp:v2
5️⃣ Check pods

kubectl get pods

3️⃣ Infrastructure Tickets
Example:
Title: Create new EC2 instance for staging environment.
Using Terraform

terraform init
terraform plan
terraform apply
Verify instance in **Amazon Web Services console.

4️⃣ CI/CD Pipeline Tickets
Example:
Title: Setup pipeline for Node.js application.
Using
GitHub Actions
Example pipeline:

name: Deploy App

on: push

jobs:
 build:
  runs-on: ubuntu-latest

  steps:
   - uses: actions/checkout@v3

   - name: Build Docker
     run: docker build -t myapp .

   - name: Push image
     run: docker push repo/myapp

5️⃣ Kubernetes Tickets
Example:
Title: Increase replicas for production service.

kubectl scale deployment myapp --replicas=5
Check

kubectl get pods

